<h2 id="section-layout">Layout</h2>

<p>Petal provides a basic layout method where you can make quick, simple column layouts. Note that this is a very 'light' implementation, so unlike some other proper grid systems, Petal not provide automatic overrides for mobile screen widths.</p>

<h3>Container</h3>
<p>Add the <code>.container</code> class to a container div where you would insert your site contents into. Usually a single page/view will have only one <code>.container</code>.</p>

<p>Container width is set as a LESS variable <code>@container-width</code> in <code>petal.less</code> file. Default value is 980px; modify the value to change fixed width.</p>

<br>

<h3>Columns</h3>
<p>Easily create column layouts for the whole page or parts of the page.</p>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-1 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-1</span></div>
</div>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-2 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-2</span></div>
	<div class="col-2 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-2</span></div>
</div>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-3 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-3</span></div>
	<div class="col-3 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-3</span></div>
	<div class="col-3 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-3</span></div>
</div>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-4 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-4</span></div>
	<div class="col-4 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-4</span></div>
	<div class="col-4 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-4</span></div>
	<div class="col-4 bg-green-l2"><span>.col-4</span></div>
</div>

<p>Place a div with the <code>.row</code> class, then insert <code>.col-<em>x</em></code> class inside to make columns, where <em>x</em> is the number of columns the row is divided into. (Supports 2,3,4 columns)</p>

<p>The default left/right padding for the columns is 15px, same as the <code>.container</code> inner paddings. To change this, modify the <code>@col-padding</code> value. It's recommended that you keep the column padding value and the container inner padding value equal.</p>

<br>

<h5>Spanned columns</h5>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-3 colspan-2 bg-blue-l2"><span>.col-3.colspan-2</span></div>
	<div class="col-3 bg-blue-l2"><span>.col-3.colspan-2</span></div>
</div>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-4 colspan-2 bg-blue-l2"><span>.col-4.colspan-2</span></div>
	<div class="col-4 bg-blue-l2"><span>.col-4</span></div>
	<div class="col-4 bg-blue-l2"><span>.col-4</span></div>
</div>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-4 bg-blue-l2"><span>.col-4</span></div>
	<div class="col-4 colspan-3 bg-blue-l2"><span>.col-4.colspan-3</span></div>
</div>

<p>Add <code>.colspan-<em>x</em></code> to column divs, where <em>x</em> is the number of columns you would 'merge' (think of a table layout).</p>

<br>

<h5>Nesting columns</h5>
<div class="row borders mb-10">
	<div class="col-3 bg-blue-l2">
		<span>.col-3</span>
		<div class="row borders">
			<div class="col-2 bg-blue-l1"><span>.col-2</span></div>
			<div class="col-2 bg-blue-l1"><span>.col-2</span></div>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="col-3 bg-green-l2">
		<span>.col-3</span>
		<div class="row borders">
			<div class="col-3 bg-green-l1"><span>.col-3</span></div>
			<div class="col-3 bg-green-l1"><span>.col-3</span></div>
			<div class="col-3 bg-green-l1"><span>.col-3</span></div>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="col-3 bg-red-l2">
		<span>.col-3</span>
		<div class="row borders">
			<div class="col-1 bg-red-l1"><span>.col-1</span></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>
<p>You can nest any columns inside columns. Just don't forget to nest <code>.row</code>s as well. </p>

<br>

<h3>Column Options (only for Flexbox method)</h3>


<p>By the looks, both methods will display exactly the same with the same settings. Benefits of using flexbox are that markup will be more cleaner because you don't need the <a href="http://nicolasgallagher.com/micro-clearfix-hack/">micro clearfix</a> hack anymore (it inserts pseudo <code>:before</code> and <code>:after</code> elements to the parent row element); 2.  </p>
<p>Make sure the browser you're developing your project for <a href="http://caniuse.com/#search=flex">has proper support for flexboxes</a>. Petal does not provide automatic table fallbacks for older browsers.</p>

<br>

<h5>Collapsed column gutters</h5>
<div class="demo-panel gray p-15">
	<div class="row mv-10">
		<div class="col-3"><div class="bg-red-l1 p-10">Column 1</div></div>
		<div class="col-3"><div class="bg-red-l1 p-10">Column 2</div></div>
		<div class="col-3"><div class="bg-red-l1 p-10">Column 3</div></div>
	</div>
	<div class="row mv-10">
		<div class="col-3 collapse-gutter stretch"><div class="bg-green-l1 p-10">Column 1 (Collapsed gutter)</div></div>
		<div class="col-3 collapse-gutter stretch"><div class="bg-green-l1 p-10">Column 2 (Collapsed gutter)</div></div>
		<div class="col-3 collapse-gutter stretch"><div class="bg-green-l1 p-10">Column 3 (Collapsed gutter)</div></div>
	</div>
</div>

<p>An optional <code>.collapse-gutter</code> class added on <code>.col-x</code> elements will 'collapse' the gutter inbetween columns by reducing the padding space to half while keeping the outer paddings on left and right. This is useful when you want to keep the global container padding value but just want to reduce the size of the gutter to be equal to the padding width. </p>

